\u002F\u002Fwww.20minutos.es\u002Fnoticia\u002F1709522\u002F0\u002Fgeneracion-perdida\u002Fjovenes-espanoles\u002Fdesempleo-estudios\u002F\"\u003Elost generation\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo; toward non-traditional jobs to make a living. In modern Spain, the linear path just does not cut it for many to get by.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoing, going&hellip;\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERents in Spain are rising \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.elmundo.es\u002Feconomia\u002Fvivienda\u002F2018\u002F05\u002F15\u002F5af9d7e7ca47414b478b4631.html\"\u003E12 times faster than salaries\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The average monthly rent rose during the first three months of 2018 to 1,025 euros ($1,167) &ndash; as high as 1,603 euros ($1,825) in Barcelona and 1,549 euros ($1,764) in Madrid.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, researchers from Spain&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.lavanguardia.com\u002Feconomia\u002F20180529\u002F443927191091\u002Fsalario-medio-espana-sueldo.html\"\u003ENational Statistics Institute\u003C\u002Fa\u003E estimated the average Spanish millennial monthly salary as 943 euros ($1,074) for aged 20 to 24; 1,323 euros ($1,506) for aged 25 to 29; and 1,612 euros ($1,835) for aged 30 to 34. At the bottom end of the range for rent, even the highest earning millennials statistically pay well beyond 50% of their monthly salary for shelter &ndash; far beyond the expert-recommended 30% upper limit.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResearchers from the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.lisdatacenter.org\u002Fwps\u002Fliswps\u002F732.pdf\"\u003EIntergenerational Commission\u003C\u002Fa\u003E at UK-based think-tank the Resolution Foundation concluded that &ldquo;millennials have substantially lower incomes than Generation X did at the same age. In Spain, for example, typical incomes for millennials in their early 30s are &ndash; so far &ndash;&nbsp;a sizeable 30% (7,000 euros) lower than they were for Generation X&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Even the highest earning millennials statistically pay well beyond 50% of their monthly salary for shelter &ndash; far beyond the expert-recommended 30% upper limit","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnd although living standards have certainly improved during the past 30 years, whether conditions are actually &ldquo;better&rdquo; becomes a bit fuzzier, according to economist Francisco Jos&eacute; Goerlich, who works at the University of Valencia. &ldquo;It is true that rising rents, especially in big cities, are an important share of expenditures, so money left for other things is, to some extent, less,&rdquo; he says.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA different flight path\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECristina Robles, 30, studied documentary film-making and interned at companies around Madrid, including Spanish national broadcaster Televisi&oacute;n Espa&ntilde;ola. Robles has also discovered that breaking into Spain&rsquo;s job market as a millennial is difficult &ndash; especially compared to her predecessors. &ldquo;Everyone is expecting you to do five different jobs in one and be paid 650 euros ($740) a month,&rdquo; she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERobles has not taken a job in media, but is instead part of La P&aacute;jara Ciclomensajer&iacute;a (The Delivery Bird), a bicycle service offering scheduled deliveries, arranged over the phone or online, and on-the-spot food deliveries which customers order via their website.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ELa P&aacute;jara was launched in September 2018 by five millennial friends &ndash; three Spaniards, a Costa Rican and an Italian. The five had previous experience working for gig-based companies, including Deliveroo, and and said they wanted to leave the restrictive model for something with more autonomy and more ethical work practices.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I think the key is that we are the owners of the cooperative and all the money is shared by us,&rdquo; says Martino Correggiari, 30. He adds that &ldquo;there are no people in between&rdquo; like other gig economy business models that rely on contractors. The heart of La P&aacute;jara, he stresses, is working for yourself.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"We love to be on the streets and ride and it&rsquo;s really cool if you think you can be paid for something you really love &ndash; Cristina Robles","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAt the moment, the riders are on their way to making 9 euros ($10.25) per hour, but with the business having started so recently, they are in what they refer to as a &ldquo;transition phase&rdquo;: building a strong client base. (Spain does not have an hourly minimum wage, but the required \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.euronews.com\u002F2018\u002F10\u002F11\u002Fspanish-politicians-edge-closer-to-increasing-minimum-wage\"\u003Emonthly minimum\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is 735 euros [$837], or 4.50 euros [$5.12] per hour for a 40-hour week).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERobles&rsquo; new work is precarious but she is still making more than she did during her last position in TV: an internship for which she was not paid anything. &ldquo;We love to be on the streets and ride and it&rsquo;s really cool if you think you can be paid for something you really love,&rdquo; she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELost generation, found\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMar&iacute;a Ramos is the co-author of The Invisible Wall, which explores the barrier between youth and independent adulthood in Spain. She says that the economic constraints faced by millennials are slowing down their progress through major life milestones. These transitions &ndash; such as becoming parents - are happening later and later and, in some cases, stalling entirely.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;This delay in Spain is very evident,&rdquo; says Ramos. &ldquo;At age 30, 78% of young people still live at home with their parents. The insecurity in the employment of the young people is enormous, and in many cases it extends throughout life.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"&nbsp; The insecurity in the employment of the young people is enormous, and in many cases it extends throughout life &ndash; Mar&iacute;a Ramos","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn 2018, Spain registered its \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.elconfidencial.com\u002Feconomia\u002F2018-06-19\u002Fespana-natalidad-poblacion_1580932\u002F\"\u003Elowest birth rate\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in 40 years: 1.3 children per mother. In 1972, it was 2.9 children. &ldquo;Millennials stay longer with their parents, marry later and have children later,&rdquo; agrees Mr Jeff&rsquo;s G&oacute;mez. &ldquo;My mother was 16 when she left home and my dad was 25.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAlong with changes in how they live, many millennials are also rethinking traditional expectations about what it means to be successful, both professionally and personally.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;People are looking for experiences more than life goals as we know them; you know, by 30 I&rsquo;m going to be married and have two dogs and hopefully a kid. People aren&rsquo;t measuring their lives on goals, they are measuring their lives on experiences\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&rdquo; says Robles. &ldquo;If this job allows us to have a decent life and enjoy what we do&hellip; then I think we&rsquo;re not doing anything wrong.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20181108-spanish-millennials-are-reshaping-their-goals-to-afford-life-10"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2018-11-27T21:47:10Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Spanish millennials are reshaping their goals to afford life","headlineShort":"'It was impossible to get a real job'","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"worklife","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":[],"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"The average Spanish millennial spends more than half of their monthly income on rent. In a country where it's hard to earn and expensive to live, something has to give.","summaryShort":"What do young Spanish people do when it’s hard to earn and expensive to live?","tag":[],"creationDateTim